<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,151,823]" pageId="7" pageNumber="220">
<emphasis box="[199,305,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="220">Abdomen</emphasis>
: Ventrite VII and speculum as in 
<figureCitation box="[682,763,151,175]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–13" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1967,1990]" captionTargetBox="[268,1396,184,1954]" captionTargetId="figure-56@6.[151,1436,167,2020]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 8–13. Male ventrite VII and speculum gastrale. 8, Gymnochthebius fossatus. 9, Ochthebius attritus. 10, Hydraena decui. 11, H. franklyni. 12, H. guadelupensis. 13, H. perkinsi. Scale = 0.1 mm." pageId="7" pageNumber="220">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
; ventrite VII subquadrate, speculum slightly separated from ventrite, moderately long. Terminal tergite as in 
<figureCitation box="[690,757,188,212]" captionStart="FIGURES 2–7" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1936,1959]" captionTargetBox="[187,1406,187,1853]" captionTargetId="figure-54@4.[151,1436,161,1915]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 2–7. Terminal male tergite. 2, Gymnochthebius fossatus. 3, Ochthebius attritus. 4, Hydraena decui. 5, H. perkinsi. 6, H. guadelupensis. 7, H. franklyni. Scale = 0.1 mm." pageId="7" pageNumber="220">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
, rounded. Male genitalia as in 
<figureCitation box="[1099,1234,188,212]" captionStart="FIGURES 31–34" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1875,1898]" captionTargetBox="[191,1349,202,1821]" captionTargetId="figure-48@15.[151,1436,143,1854]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 31–34. Male genitalia. 31, Hydraena guadelupensis (lateral view). 32, H. guadelupensis (ventral view). 33, H. franklyni (lateral view, holotype). 34, H. franklyni (ventral view, holotype). Scale = 0.1 mm." pageId="7" pageNumber="220">Figs. 33–34</figureCitation>
; main piece stout, strongly dilated both in lateral and ventral views; with three distinct processes at the apex, with the gonopore bearing process elongate, and the other two lobe-like; parameres inserted near 0.5 length of main piece, lightly widened apically, right paramere inserted more proximally than left one.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,151,823]" pageId="7" pageNumber="220">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,295,332,356]" pageId="7" pageNumber="220">Female:</emphasis>
Similar to the male in shape and size; Pro- and metatibia not modified; gonocoxite as in 
<figureCitation box="[1302,1385,332,356]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–26" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1761,1784]" captionTargetBox="[218,1407,192,1728]" captionTargetId="figure-70@11.[151,1436,157,1774]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 21–26. Gonocoxite and last female tergite. 21, gonocoxite of Hydraena franklyni. 22, last female tergite of H. franklyni. 23, gonocoxite of H. guadelupensis. 24, last female tergite of H. guadelupensis. 25, gonocoxite of H. perkinsi. 26, last female tergite of H. perkinsi. Scale = 0.1 mm." pageId="7" pageNumber="220">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
; last tergite as in 
<figureCitation box="[287,369,367,391]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–26" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1761,1784]" captionTargetBox="[218,1407,192,1728]" captionTargetId="figure-70@11.[151,1436,157,1774]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 21–26. Gonocoxite and last female tergite. 21, gonocoxite of Hydraena franklyni. 22, last female tergite of H. franklyni. 23, gonocoxite of H. guadelupensis. 24, last female tergite of H. guadelupensis. 25, gonocoxite of H. perkinsi. 26, last female tergite of H. perkinsi. Scale = 0.1 mm." pageId="7" pageNumber="220">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
; spermatheca as in 
<figureCitation box="[586,720,367,391]" captionStart="FIGURES 45–55" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1914,1937]" captionTargetBox="[188,1418,191,1898]" captionTargetId="figure-82@20.[151,1436,151,1977]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 45–55. Spermathecae. 45, G.fossatus(lateral view). 46, G. fossatus (ventral view). 47, O. attritus (ventral view). 48, H. decui (lateral view). 49, H. decui (ventral view). 50, H. franklyni (lateral view). 51, H. franklyni (ventral view). 52, H. guadelupensis (lateral view). 53, H. guadelupensis (ventral view). 54, H. perkinsi (lateral view). 55, H. perkinsi (ventral view). Scale = 0.1 mm." pageId="7" pageNumber="220">Figs. 50–51</figureCitation>
, with two separated sclerotized pieces, the caudal one c-shaped; spermathecal duct enlarged distally.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="220" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,151,823]" pageId="7" pageNumber="220">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,469,439,464]" pageId="7" pageNumber="220">Differential diagnosis:</emphasis>
This species is unique among the 
<taxonomicName box="[897,1009,440,464]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="220" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[897,1009,440,464]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="220">Hydraena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the New World in having an aedeagus with a strongly widened main piece (
<figureCitation box="[681,820,476,500]" captionStart="FIGURES 31–34" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1875,1898]" captionTargetBox="[191,1349,202,1821]" captionTargetId="figure-48@15.[151,1436,143,1854]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 31–34. Male genitalia. 31, Hydraena guadelupensis (lateral view). 32, H. guadelupensis (ventral view). 33, H. franklyni (lateral view, holotype). 34, H. franklyni (ventral view, holotype). Scale = 0.1 mm." pageId="7" pageNumber="220">Figs. 33–34</figureCitation>
). The closest aedeagus in shape is that of 
<taxonomicName authority="Perkins, 1980" authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="1980" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="220" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spangleri">
<emphasis box="[1295,1436,476,500]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="220">H. spangleri</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Perkins, P. D." box="[151,308,511,535]" pageId="7" pageNumber="220" pagination="3 - 554" refId="ref9611" refString="Perkins, P. D. (1980) Aquatic beetles of the family Hydraenidae in the Western Hemisphere: classification, biogeography and inferred phylogeny (Insecta: Coleoptera). Quaestiones Entomologicae, 16, 3 - 554." type="journal article" year="1980">Perkins, 1980</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, since both species have a wide main piece with three processes at the apex. Both species have the right paramere inserted more proximally than the left, but the parameres have very different lengths in the two species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="220" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,151,823]" pageId="7" pageNumber="220">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,620,644]" pageId="7" pageNumber="220">Etymology:</emphasis>
The species epithet is a noun in the genitive case after Franklyn Cala-Riquelme, excellent colleague and friend, who assisted in fieldwork during several collecting trips.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="220" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,151,823]" box="[199,1151,691,716]" pageId="7" pageNumber="220">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,354,691,716]" pageId="7" pageNumber="220">Distribution:</emphasis>
Currently known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[718,766,692,716]" pageId="7" pageNumber="220">type</typeStatus>
locality in eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[980,1039,692,716]" name="Cuba" pageId="7" pageNumber="220">Cuba</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[1054,1138,692,716]" captionStart="FIGURES 56–58" captionStartId="21.[151,264,1977,2000]" captionTargetBox="[279,1313,183,1967]" captionTargetId="figure-63@21.[264,1325,169,1988]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURES 56–58. Distribution maps for all species of Hydraenidae in eastern Cuba. 56, squares = G. fossatus, circles = O. attritus. 57, squares = H. franklyni, circles = H. guadelupensis. 58, squares = H. decui, circles = H. perkinsi." pageId="7" pageNumber="220">Fig. 57</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,151,823]" pageId="7" pageNumber="220">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,300,727,752]" pageId="7" pageNumber="220">Habitat:</emphasis>
Hygropetric as in 
<figureCitation box="[511,594,727,751]" captionStart="FIGURES 59–61" captionStartId="22.[151,264,1907,1930]" captionTargetBox="[193,1398,193,1897]" captionTargetId="figure-85@22.[193,1398,193,1897]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 59–61. Habitats of Hydraenidae species. 59, habitat and type locality of H. franklyni. Gran Piedra, Santiago de Cuba (Photo by A. Deler-Hernández, 04-III-2012). 60, habitat of G.fossatus and H. perkinsi. Temporary pool, Dos Caminos, San Luis, Santiago de Cuba (Photo by A. Deler-Hernández, 20-VII-2011). 61, habitat of H. decui. Stream, Gran Piedra, Santiago de Cuba (Photo by L. O. Mélian, 09-XI-2011)." pageId="7" pageNumber="220">Fig. 59</figureCitation>
. This new species has been collected on sunny, exposed, humid rock faces (seepages) and among associated patches of the hornwort 
<taxonomicName authority="(Steph.) Hassel" authorityName="Hassel" baseAuthorityName="Steph." box="[798,1202,764,788]" class="Anthocerotopsida" family="Notothyladaceae" genus="Phaeoceros" kingdom="Plantae" order="Notothyladales" pageId="7" pageNumber="220" phylum="Anthocerotophyta" rank="species" species="wrightii">
<emphasis box="[798,1025,764,788]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="220">Phaeoceros wrightii</emphasis>
(Steph.) Hässel
</taxonomicName>
(Anthocerophyta) in a well preserved rainforest habitat at 
<quantity box="[566,650,799,823]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.144" pageId="7" pageNumber="220" unit="m" value="1144.0">1144 m</quantity>
a.s.l.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
